block content

  +state('Michigan', '/assets/images/flag-michigan.svg', 'The Great Lake State', 'January 26, 1837')

  .intro
    p The current Michigan flag is the third version for the state. Descriptions of the first two flags exist, but their specific designs have been lost to history.
    p The first Michigan flag was notable in its depiction of Governor Stevens T. Mason. He is the only real person besides George Washington to appear on a state flag.
    p Michigan’s flag now follows the common pattern of a field of blue charged with the state coat of arms.
    p This version was officially adopted June 26, 1911.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Flag design
      p The Michigan flag features a field of blue with the state coat of arms at the center.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan.svg')

  .guide.wide
    .content
      h2 Iconography
      ul.visual.icon-list
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-elk-moose.svg')
          h4 Elk & Moose
          p Although said to be borrowed from the Hudson’s Bay Company coat of arms, the elk and moose have become symbols for Michigan’s natural beauty.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-eagle.svg')
          h4 Eagle
          p Borrowed from the Great Seal of the U.S. and representing the nation, the eagle symbolizes peace and strength, clutching an olive branch and a bunch of arrows.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-man.svg')
          h4 Armed man
          p Upon a Michigan peninsula, a man waves with his weapon pointed toward the sky, a visualization of the word “Tuebor” inscribed above.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-tuebor.svg')
          h4 Tuebor
          p Translated from Latin, “Tuebor” means “I will defend.” While the armed man is peaceful, he is equipt to fight if needed.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-e-pluribus-unum.svg')
          h4 E Pluribus Unum
          p Also borrowed from the Great Seal, “E Pluribus Unum” translates to “From many, one” and represents the U.S. as a single nation made up of states.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-michigan-icon-motto.svg')
          h4 Motto
          p Michigan’s state motto translates to “If You Seek a Pleasant Peninsula, Look About You.”

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Coat of Arms
      p Established in 1835, the Michigan coat of arms bears resemblance to the coat of arms of the #[a(href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company#/media/File:HBC-coa.JPG') Hudson’s Bay Company], which also features an elk and moose as supports.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/coat-of-arms-michigan.jpg')

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Colors
      p Only azure and white (argent) are specifically mentioned in the statute for the coat of arms. No colors are specified for the flag.
